#Text=United States Senate candidate Al Franken increases lead in recount
#Text=Wednesday , April 8 , 2009
#Text=With 351 additional ballots counted , Al Franken has increased his lead over former Minnesota Sen. Norm Coleman from 225 to 312 votes , local news agencies reported Tuesday .
#Text=Al Franken
#Text=Image : Вени Марковски .
#Text=Norm Coleman U.S. Senate photo
#Text=In November , the results of the 2008 United States Senate election in Minnesota showed Republican Norm Coleman with a 215 vote lead over the Democratic challenger Franken .
#Text=The close margin — less than 0.0075 percent — triggered an automatic recount which resulted in Franken leading by 225 votes , the total ratified by the Minnesota Canvasing Board January 5 .
#Text=The Coleman campaign filed a motion January 6 in court to block the certification of Franken 's victory and prevent Franken from taking a seat in the United States Senate .
#Text=On March 31 , a three-judge panel hearing the case ordered 400 additional ballots be considered for counting .
#Text=State elections director Gary Poser read the results of 351 of those ballots to a hushed courtroom in St. Paul .
#Text=Franken received 198 votes , while Coleman received 111 .
#Text=Third-party candidate Dean Barkley and other candidates got the 42 remaining votes .
#Text=Poser was supervised closely by Minnesota Secretary of State Mark Ritchie , Franken lawyer Marc Elias and Coleman lawyer Tony Trimble .

#Text=With his case resting on the outcome of the unopened ballots , Coleman can no longer win mathematically , as he can now receive a maximum of 49 votes yet to be counted , which would not erase Franken 's lead .
#Text=Franken 's campaign said the result told the story .
#Text=" The result confirms what we knew going in , which is that more Minnesotans voted for Al Franken than Norm Coleman , " Elias told reporters .
#Text=" That was the case when we recounted the ballots the first time , and it 's now the case after the election contest .

#Text= It should have been about 10 times more than that , " Ginsberg said .

column1: #Text=" We will be appealing this to the Minnesota Supreme Court . "
#Text=Ginsberg went on to say that Tuesday 's decision was not a large one .
#Text=" What happened today in the sphere of this election is really inconsequential , " Ginsberg said .
#Text=" What we 've been saying is there 's a much bigger pool of ballots that should be opened . "
#Text=An election certificate requires both the signature of Ritchie and governor Tim Pawlenty .

#Text=Pawlenty has n't said whether or not he would sign the certificate though he did say that if Coleman appeals the Minnesota Supreme Court decision , the governor would be unable to sign the certificate until any federal legal process is concluded .
